00:50:14.199 --> 00:50:18.840
I was a big Tableau user, but Tableau has limitations. The one

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:22.600
limitation is that you cannot do advanced analytics in Tableau.

00:50:22.600 --> 00:50:27.159
You can do visualizations, you can slice and dice data. The

00:50:27.159 --> 00:50:30.600
most advanced data science you can do in Tableau right now is

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:33.879
you can do regression. So you can fit a simple line to your

00:50:33.879 --> 00:50:38.040
data set. And that is the limit of what you can do. But if you

00:50:38.040 --> 00:50:40.360
want to use some of the algorithms, for example, if you

00:50:40.360 --> 00:50:45.159
want to use the segmentation or the comorbidity association

00:50:45.159 --> 00:50:48.439
rules that I've used here, then Tableau cannot do that. It can

00:50:48.439 --> 00:50:51.639
make your data look pretty, but it cannot do that analysis. And

00:50:51.639 --> 00:50:55.719
to do that analysis, you will have to use either R or Python

00:50:56.439 --> 00:51:00.840
Flask. Within R and Python, I feel like most of the research

00:51:00.840 --> 00:51:04.679
community, people like me who were in research, we tend to

00:51:04.679 --> 00:51:09.479
publish all of our research as R packages. So you would usually

00:51:09.479 --> 00:51:12.760
see things coming out of research going into R first. And

00:51:12.760 --> 00:51:16.520
if they're very useful for industry, there'll be a Python

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:21.320
package that is now copying that R package. So with Shiny or

00:51:21.320 --> 00:51:24.360
Flask, you can use the latest and greatest data science

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:27.560
advanced analytics, along with visualization, the

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:31.159
visualization might not look as neat as a Tableau, just because

00:51:31.159 --> 00:51:34.199
it's been designed by like professionals, but it will still

00:51:34.199 --> 00:51:37.159
be more advanced, you can do these analysis, which are more

00:51:37.159 --> 00:51:38.439
complicated in R.

00:51:40.360 --> 00:51:42.919
Thank you, Jay, that's really helpful. I know, you know, that

00:51:42.919 --> 00:51:46.679
question seems to come up on quite a few meetups, too. So

00:51:47.879 --> 00:51:51.399
maybe it'd be helpful for us to even have a full a longer talk

00:51:51.399 --> 00:51:55.800
on that, too. Another question, I know, we have just a few more

