minutes here. But should age asked, Hey, Jay, have you

00:52:00.199 --> 00:52:03.320
encountered scenarios where you want to run clustering on big

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:07.399
data sets, upwards of 10 million rows from within Shiny?

00:52:10.199 --> 00:52:13.800
So, so the one thing I would say is that most of the Shiny apps

00:52:13.800 --> 00:52:18.600
that I've shown you, it tends to run on smaller data sets. For

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:22.760
bigger data sets, Shiny for for the current for the knowledge

00:52:22.760 --> 00:52:25.080
that the limited knowledge that I have in the use that I have

00:52:25.080 --> 00:52:29.239
had, the scalability tends to be an issue later on. Now,

00:52:29.239 --> 00:52:31.879
recently, there have been new packages that you can use to

00:52:31.879 --> 00:52:35.879
paralyze the analysis. And you can use delay methodology. So

00:52:35.879 --> 00:52:40.679
you can, you don't have to perform the analysis. Right,

00:52:40.679 --> 00:52:43.399
then you can use a catch or you can delay the analysis later on.

00:52:43.399 --> 00:52:47.320
And that makes the flow, the user experience faster. But if

00:52:47.320 --> 00:52:51.639
you are trying to use big data analysis, then Shiny might not

00:52:51.639 --> 00:52:56.600
be the best idea shortage. Or it might be maybe I don't know.

00:52:56.600 --> 00:53:00.439
But for those kind of analysis, trying to build a live app, you

00:53:00.439 --> 00:53:02.919
tend to work better with some of the other big data

00:53:02.919 --> 00:53:06.360
methodologies. So if you're running your analysis on, say,

00:53:06.360 --> 00:53:09.879
Spark, then you can use things that that go on top of a Spark

00:53:09.879 --> 00:53:12.760
analysis. And you can use dashboarding there to analyze

00:53:12.760 --> 00:53:15.080
those process flows, and they'll be much more efficient. And

